definition: "Serum calcium is one of the most tightly regulated minerals in the body, maintained within a narrow range (8.5–10.5 mg/dL) through an exquisitely sensitive hormonal control system. The primary regulators are parathyroid hormone (PTH), calcitriol (active vitamin D, or 1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D3), and calcitonin. PTH is released by the four parathyroid glands (small glands embedded in the thyroid) when serum calcium falls, and it raises calcium by stimulating bone resorption (releasing calcium from bone), increasing renal calcium reabsorption (reducing urinary calcium loss), and stimulating calcitriol production (which increases intestinal calcium absorption). Calcitriol amplifies PTH's effects on intestinal absorption and bone. Calcitonin, released by thyroid C cells when calcium rises, modestly inhibits bone resorption. Of the total body calcium, 99% is stored in bone and teeth; only 1% circulates in blood. Of the circulating calcium, approximately 40–45% is bound to albumin (inactive), 5–10% is complexed to other anions, and 45–50% is ionized (free) — the only biologically active fraction. Because albumin-bound calcium varies with albumin levels, serum calcium must be corrected for albumin concentration, or ionized calcium (which is unaffected by albumin changes) should be measured directly."
why_it_matters: "Calcium is so tightly regulated that even small persistent deviations from the midpoint of the normal range are biologically meaningful — they indicate that the regulatory machinery is under strain or compromised. Persistently elevated calcium (hypercalcemia) is most commonly caused by primary hyperparathyroidism (one or more overactive parathyroid glands) — a condition affecting approximately 1 in 500 adults that is frequently diagnosed incidentally through routine lab work, often in perimenopausal and postmenopausal women. Primary hyperparathyroidism slowly depletes bone density, raises cardiovascular risk, and produces fatigue, kidney stones, and cognitive effects — often for years before diagnosis. Persistently low calcium (hypocalcemia) signals vitamin D deficiency, hypoparathyroidism (often from prior thyroid or neck surgery), or malabsorption. In longevity medicine, serum calcium also flags a commonly underdiagnosed condition — hypercalcemia of malignancy — in which certain cancers secrete PTH-related protein or directly stimulate bone resorption. Any unexplained calcium above 10.5 mg/dL requires investigation."

