longevity_notes: "Serum calcium must always be interpreted in context: albumin level (calcium appears low in hypoalbuminemia — use corrected calcium = measured calcium + 0.8 × (4 – albumin g/dL)), PTH, and vitamin D. A calcium of 10.3 mg/dL with a low PTH suggests a non-parathyroid cause of hypercalcemia (malignancy, sarcoidosis, vitamin D toxicity). A calcium of 10.3 mg/dL with a high PTH confirms primary hyperparathyroidism. A calcium of 10.3 mg/dL with a very high PTH despite hypercalcemia should prompt investigation for tertiary hyperparathyroidism or familial hypocalciuric hypercalcemia. The longevity-optimal range of 9.0–9.8 mg/dL represents the midpoint of the physiologically normal range — neither pushing the upper boundary (where PTH may be suppressed inappropriately) nor the lower boundary (where compensatory PTH elevation suggests vitamin D or calcium inadequacy)."
