<section class="bm-section">
<h2>The Most Tightly Regulated Mineral — and What Deviations Signal</h2>

<p>The human body defends serum calcium with a level of hormonal precision that rivals blood pH regulation. Normal serum calcium falls within a narrow range of approximately 8.5–10.5 mg/dL, and the regulatory system — primarily PTH and active vitamin D — responds to deviations within seconds to minutes. This tight regulation exists because calcium is indispensable for muscle contraction (including cardiac muscle), nerve impulse transmission, blood clotting, and enzyme function across virtually every organ system. Levels outside the normal range, if sustained, produce immediate physiological consequences.</p>

<p>The practical implication for longevity monitoring is that when serum calcium persistently deviates from the midpoint of its normal range — either upward or downward — the regulatory machinery is telling you something meaningful. A calcium consistently running at 10.2–10.4 mg/dL is not just "at the upper end of normal" — it means the parathyroid glands are failing to suppress appropriately, which is the definition of primary hyperparathyroidism in its early stages. A calcium consistently at 8.5–8.7 mg/dL with elevated PTH means the body is actively mobilizing calcium from bone to maintain even this marginal level.</p>
</section>

<section class="bm-section">
<h2>Primary Hyperparathyroidism: The Underdiagnosed Common Endocrine Disease</h2>

<p>Primary hyperparathyroidism — caused in 85% of cases by a single benign parathyroid adenoma secreting excess PTH — is the most common cause of mild hypercalcemia in ambulatory adults and one of the most commonly missed endocrine diagnoses. It affects approximately 1 in 500 adults, with peak incidence in postmenopausal women.</p>

<p>In its typical modern presentation, primary hyperparathyroidism is "asymptomatic" — meaning there are no dramatic symptoms, but there are insidious effects accumulating over years: progressive loss of bone density (preferentially cortical bone, which is PTH-sensitive), increased risk of kidney stones, fatigue, cognitive blunting, and elevated cardiovascular risk through vascular calcification mechanisms.</p>

<p>The diagnostic algorithm is straightforward: calcium above 10.2 mg/dL on two measurements → check PTH. If PTH is elevated or inappropriately normal (PTH should be completely suppressed when calcium is elevated), primary hyperparathyroidism is confirmed and endocrinology referral is warranted. The definitive treatment is surgical removal of the adenoma, which normalizes calcium and PTH within hours and stops further bone loss progression. <sup><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24593895/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">1</a></sup></p>

